</ul><hr><p><b>P.S.</b></p><p>In 2018, my colleague Julie Beck did a great <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/bo-burnham-on-the-incredible-honesty-of-middle-schoolers-online/566579/?utm_source=feed">interview</a> with Bo Burnham about his movie <i>Eighth Grade</i>. I’ll leave you with his description of that particular year of life: “I think eighth grade is a time where your self-awareness is just flicked on like a light,” he told Julie. “All of a sudden you look at yourself and you’re like, ‘Oh my God, have I been this the whole time?’ And then you’re trying to build a parachute as you’re falling.</p><p>“There’s a transparency to the way the kids socialize at that age that I think is very beautiful. Who you are, who you’re trying to be, and how you’re trying to be it are all very clean and clear and visible. You’re not really fooling anybody.”</p><p>— Isabel</p>